<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="yes"?>
<bug>
    <id>610461</id>
    <title>Sites with advertising give repeated errors for "xpcom_core.dll file not found."</title>
    <description>
        <paragraph id="2">
            <sentence id="2.1">Sites with advertising (Flash or Shockwave, I believe) give repeated errors for "xpcom_core.</sentence>
            <sentence id="2.2">dll file not found."</sentence>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph id="3">
            <sentence id="3.1">I've tried uninstalling Firefox many times, and it never fixes the problem.</sentence>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph id="4">
            <sentence id="4.1">I checked the user group postings, and 42 people report that they have this same issue.</sentence>
            <sentence id="4.2">if 42 report it, I have to think that 42,000 must have the problem.</sentence>
            <sentence id="4.3">I've had it for at least a year.</sentence>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph id="5">
            <sentence id="5.1">http://support.mozilla.com/en-US/questions/667781?s=xpcom_core.dll&amp;as=s</sentence>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph id="7">
            <sentence id="7.1">Steps to Reproduce:</sentence>
            <sentence id="7.2">1 Go to a site with advertising.</sentence>
            <sentence id="7.3">AOL.com, for example.</sentence>
            <sentence id="7.4">2 For each instance of a Flash ad (guessing; basically, ads with animation), I get an error message.</sentence>
            <sentence id="7.5">3 Uninstalling (but keeping user settings), and then re-installing should take care of the problem.</sentence>
            <sentence id="7.6">Actual Results:</sentence>
            <sentence id="7.7">Uninstalling and re-installing had no effect.</sentence>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph id="8">
            <sentence id="8.1">Expected Results:  
Uninstalling and re-installing had no effect.</sentence>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph id="9">
            <sentence id="9.1">My understanding - from the following link - is that this problem goes back to Firefox 2.0.0.x.</sentence>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph id="10">
            <sentence id="10.1">http://support.mozilla.com/en-US/questions/667781?s=xpcom_core.dll&amp;as=s</sentence>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph id="11">
            <sentence id="11.1">"The file xpcom_core.</sentence>
            <sentence id="11.2">dll was last used in Firefox 2.0.0.x versions and is no longer present and used in current Firefox versions.</sentence>
            <sentence id="11.3">You seem to have a program or an add-on that is still looking for that file.</sentence>
            <sentence id="11.4">You will have to uninstall that program."</sentence>
        </paragraph>
    </description>
</bug>
